---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="NTRIP">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/protocols">Protocols</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>NTRIP</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Protocols · Article 4 of 5</span>
        <h1>NTRIP</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          NTRIP — Networked Transport of RTCM via Internet Protocol — is how GNSS correction
          data travels from reference stations to rovers over the internet. It is the plumbing
          behind every network RTK service, CORS network and commercial correction stream in use
          today. Understanding it explains why your RTK connection works the way it does.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>8 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#architecture">Architecture — three roles</a></li>
          <li><a href="#protocol">Protocol basics</a></li>
          <li><a href="#sourcetable">The source table</a></li>
          <li><a href="#versions">NTRIP v1 vs v2</a></li>
          <li><a href="#connection">Connecting a rover</a></li>
          <li><a href="#latency">Latency and bandwidth</a></li>
          <li><a href="#public-casters">Public NTRIP casters</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="architecture">Architecture — three roles</h2>
      <p>
        NTRIP defines three distinct roles that work together to deliver corrections:
      </p>

      <div class="roles-diagram">
        <div class="role role-server">
          <div class="role-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="role-title">NTRIP Server</div>
          <div class="role-sub">(NtripServer)</div>
          <div class="role-desc">
            A reference station receiver or network processing engine that generates RTCM
            corrections and pushes them to the caster. One server per correction stream
            (mountpoint). The server authenticates to the caster with a password.
          </div>
          <div class="role-example">Example: A Trimble SPS986 base station pushing MT 1074/1094 to a caster.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="role-arrow">→ push →</div>
        <div class="role role-caster">
          <div class="role-icon">🖥️</div>
          <div class="role-title">NTRIP Caster</div>
          <div class="role-sub">(NtripCaster)</div>
          <div class="role-desc">
            The central server. Receives streams from servers, maintains a source table listing
            all available mountpoints, and relays streams to connecting clients.
            Acts as the multiplexer — one caster can serve thousands of clients simultaneously.
          </div>
          <div class="role-example">Example: rtk2go.com, euref-ip.net, SNIP caster software.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="role-arrow">→ pull →</div>
        <div class="role role-client">
          <div class="role-icon">🚗</div>
          <div class="role-title">NTRIP Client</div>
          <div class="role-sub">(NtripClient)</div>
          <div class="role-desc">
            The rover receiver or software that connects to the caster, requests a specific
            mountpoint and receives the RTCM stream. The client typically sends its approximate
            position (GGA sentence) to the caster so VRS systems can generate location-specific
            corrections.
          </div>
          <div class="role-example">Example: u-blox receiver with SIM card, RTKLIB str2str, SW Maps app.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="protocol">Protocol basics</h2>
      <p>
        NTRIP is built on top of <strong>HTTP/1.1</strong> (version 1) or HTTP/2 (version 2).
        This was a deliberate choice — HTTP is universally routable through firewalls and proxies,
        making NTRIP deployable anywhere with internet access.
      </p>
      <p>
        The client connection flow:
      </p>

      <ol class="steps">
        <li>
          <strong>TCP connection:</strong> Client connects to the caster's IP address and port
          (default: <code>2101</code>). This is a standard TCP socket connection.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>HTTP GET request:</strong> Client sends an HTTP GET for the desired mountpoint,
          with Base64-encoded credentials in the Authorization header:
          <div class="code-inline">GET /MOUNTPOINT HTTP/1.1<br>Host: caster.example.com:2101<br>Authorization: Basic dXNlcjpwYXNz<br>Ntrip-Version: Ntrip/2.0<br>User-Agent: NTRIP MyApp/1.0</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Caster response:</strong> If authenticated and mountpoint is active, caster
          responds with HTTP 200 and begins streaming RTCM data as the response body.
          The connection stays open indefinitely — this is a persistent streaming connection.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>GGA upload (optional):</strong> For VRS mountpoints, the client periodically
          sends its current GGA sentence to the caster (typically every 5–30 s). The caster
          uses this to generate location-specific corrections.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>RTCM reception:</strong> Client reads raw bytes from the socket, parses RTCM
          frames, validates CRC-24Q and feeds corrections to the GNSS engine.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="sourcetable">The source table</h2>
      <p>
        Before connecting to a mountpoint, a client should fetch the caster's
        <strong>source table</strong> — a list of all available correction streams.
        Request it with an HTTP GET for the root path:
      </p>

      <div class="code-block">
        <div class="code-title">Fetch source table</div>
        <pre><code>GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: caster.example.com:2101
Ntrip-Version: Ntrip/2.0
User-Agent: NTRIP MyApp/1.0</code></pre>
      </div>

      <p>
        The response is a plain-text table with one record per available stream.
        Each <code>STR</code> line describes a mountpoint:
      </p>

      <div class="code-block">
        <div class="code-title">Source table excerpt</div>
        <pre><code>SOURCETABLE 200 OK
STR;ALGO0;Algonquin;RTCM 3.3;1074(1),1084(1),1094(1),1005(0.1);2;GPS+GLO+GAL;SNIP;CAN;45.96;-78.07;1;0;sNTRIP;none;B;N;9600;
STR;OSLS0;Oslo;RTCM 3.2;1074(1),1094(1),1005(0.1);2;GPS+GAL;BKG;NOR;59.91;10.72;1;0;rNTRIP;none;B;N;9600;
ENDSOURCETABLE</code></pre>
      </div>

      <p>
        The semicolon-delimited fields in each STR line contain:
      </p>

      <div class="sourcetable-fields">
        <div class="sf-row sf-header">
          <span>Field</span>
          <span>Example</span>
          <span>Description</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Mountpoint</span>
          <span><code>ALGO0</code></span>
          <span>Unique name used in the GET request URL path</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Identifier</span>
          <span><code>Algonquin</code></span>
          <span>Human-readable station name</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Format</span>
          <span><code>RTCM 3.3</code></span>
          <span>Data format and version</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row sf-important">
          <span>Format details</span>
          <span><code>1074(1),1094(1)</code></span>
          <span>Message types and update rates in Hz — essential for checking compatibility</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Carrier</span>
          <span><code>2</code></span>
          <span>0=no phase, 1=L1 only, 2=L1+L2</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Nav system</span>
          <span><code>GPS+GLO+GAL</code></span>
          <span>Constellations provided</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Country</span>
          <span><code>CAN</code></span>
          <span>ISO 3-letter country code</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Latitude / Longitude</span>
          <span><code>45.96;-78.07</code></span>
          <span>Approximate position — use to select nearest mountpoint</span>
        </div>
        <div class="sf-row">
          <span>Bitrate</span>
          <span><code>9600</code></span>
          <span>Nominal stream bitrate in bps</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="versions">NTRIP v1 vs v2</h2>

      <div class="version-compare">
        <div class="ver-card">
          <div class="ver-name">NTRIP v1 (2004)</div>
          <div class="ver-items">
            <div class="ver-item good">✓ Universally supported — every receiver and caster</div>
            <div class="ver-item good">✓ Simple — pure HTTP/1.0 GET, no keep-alive</div>
            <div class="ver-item bad">✗ No chunked transfer — some HTTP proxies buffer the stream</div>
            <div class="ver-item bad">✗ No bidirectional data — GGA sent via separate workaround</div>
            <div class="ver-item bad">✗ Uses non-standard HTTP response "ICY 200 OK" instead of "HTTP/1.1 200 OK"</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ver-card">
          <div class="ver-name">NTRIP v2 (2009)</div>
          <div class="ver-items">
            <div class="ver-item good">✓ Proper HTTP/1.1 — compatible with proxies and load balancers</div>
            <div class="ver-item good">✓ Chunked transfer encoding — data flows cleanly through HTTP infrastructure</div>
            <div class="ver-item good">✓ Bidirectional — client can send GGA in request body</div>
            <div class="ver-item good">✓ UDP transport option for lower latency</div>
            <div class="ver-item bad">✗ Not universally supported by older receivers and embedded clients</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Which to use:</strong> Default to NTRIP v2 if your receiver supports it.
          Fall back to v1 if you encounter connection issues — some corporate firewalls and
          cellular gateways block or buffer the non-standard v1 response. Most public casters
          support both versions simultaneously.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="connection">Connecting a rover</h2>
      <p>
        The parameters needed to connect a rover to an NTRIP caster:
      </p>

      <div class="connection-params">
        <div class="cp-row">
          <div class="cp-param">Caster host</div>
          <div class="cp-example"><code>rtk2go.com</code></div>
          <div class="cp-desc">IP address or hostname of the NTRIP caster</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cp-row">
          <div class="cp-param">Port</div>
          <div class="cp-example"><code>2101</code></div>
          <div class="cp-desc">Default NTRIP port. Some casters use 443 (HTTPS) or custom ports.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cp-row cp-important">
          <div class="cp-param">Mountpoint</div>
          <div class="cp-example"><code>ALGO0</code></div>
          <div class="cp-desc">The specific correction stream to subscribe to. Choose based on location and message types needed.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cp-row">
          <div class="cp-param">Username</div>
          <div class="cp-example"><code>user@email.com</code></div>
          <div class="cp-desc">Many public casters accept any username. Commercial casters require a subscription account.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cp-row">
          <div class="cp-param">Password</div>
          <div class="cp-example"><code>••••••••</code></div>
          <div class="cp-desc">For public casters (rtk2go), any password is accepted. Commercial services provide credentials with subscription.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="cp-row">
          <div class="cp-param">GGA upload</div>
          <div class="cp-example"><code>Every 5 s</code></div>
          <div class="cp-desc">Required for VRS mountpoints. The caster uses your approximate position to tailor corrections. Not needed for single physical station mountpoints.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="latency">Latency and bandwidth</h2>
      <p>
        Correction latency — the delay between a measurement being made at the reference station
        and the correction arriving at the rover — directly affects RTK performance.
        Each source of delay adds up:
      </p>

      <div class="latency-breakdown">
        <div class="lat-row">
          <div class="lat-source">Reference station processing</div>
          <div class="lat-bar"><div class="lat-fill" style="width:15%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.5);">~50 ms</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="lat-row">
          <div class="lat-source">RTCM encoding + TCP send</div>
          <div class="lat-bar"><div class="lat-fill" style="width:10%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.5);">~30 ms</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="lat-row">
          <div class="lat-source">Internet transit (cellular)</div>
          <div class="lat-bar"><div class="lat-fill" style="width:20%; background:rgba(251,191,36,0.5);">~80 ms</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="lat-row">
          <div class="lat-source">Caster relay</div>
          <div class="lat-bar"><div class="lat-fill" style="width:5%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.5);">~10 ms</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="lat-row">
          <div class="lat-source">Rover TCP receive + parse</div>
          <div class="lat-bar"><div class="lat-fill" style="width:10%; background:rgba(0,212,170,0.5);">~20 ms</div></div>
        </div>
        <div class="lat-total">Typical total: 200 – 500 ms on LTE · 500 ms – 2 s on 3G · &gt;2 s on satellite internet</div>
      </div>

      <p>
        For most RTK applications, latency under 1 second is acceptable. The RTCM RRC (Range
        Rate Correction) compensates for slow correction drift. Latency above 2 seconds
        noticeably degrades RTK performance — the rover's position solution oscillates as
        stale corrections are applied.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Cellular dead zones:</strong> If your rover moves into an area without cellular
          coverage, the NTRIP connection drops. Most RTK receivers coast on the last received
          corrections for 30–60 seconds before degrading to float or standalone. Plan survey
          routes to avoid extended gaps — or use an L-band correction service that does not
          depend on cellular connectivity.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="public-casters">Public NTRIP casters</h2>
      <p>
        Several public and semi-public NTRIP casters provide free or low-cost corrections:
      </p>

      <div class="casters-grid">
        <div class="caster-card">
          <div class="caster-name">rtk2go.com</div>
          <div class="caster-badge free">Free</div>
          <div class="caster-desc">
            Community-run caster aggregating private base stations worldwide. Highly variable
            quality and availability — streams are contributed voluntarily. No SLA.
            Good for testing and development. Use any email as username, any password.
          </div>
          <div class="caster-detail"><strong>Port:</strong> 2101 · <strong>Auth:</strong> Any credentials</div>
        </div>
        <div class="caster-card">
          <div class="caster-name">EUREF-IP / BKG</div>
          <div class="caster-badge free">Free (registration)</div>
          <div class="caster-desc">
            European Reference Frame network operated by BKG (Germany). High-quality CORS
            stations across Europe. Registration required for credentials. Provides RINEX
            data via FTP and RTCM via NTRIP.
          </div>
          <div class="caster-detail"><strong>Host:</strong> euref-ip.net · <strong>Port:</strong> 2101</div>
        </div>
        <div class="caster-card">
          <div class="caster-name">NOAA CORS (NGS)</div>
          <div class="caster-badge free">Free</div>
          <div class="caster-desc">
            US National Geodetic Survey Continuously Operating Reference Station network.
            Covers the USA. Real-time RTCM streams and RINEX data available.
            Free registration at ngs.noaa.gov.
          </div>
          <div class="caster-detail"><strong>Host:</strong> ntrip.ngs.noaa.gov · <strong>Port:</strong> 443</div>
        </div>
        <div class="caster-card">
          <div class="caster-name">IGS Real-Time Service</div>
          <div class="caster-badge free">Free</div>
          <div class="caster-desc">
            IGS real-time data and SSR correction streams for PPP and PPP-RTK research.
            Provides IGS-RT orbit and clock corrections (MT 4076) in addition to raw
            station observations. Registration via IGS.
          </div>
          <div class="caster-detail"><strong>Host:</strong> ntrip.igs-ip.net · <strong>Port:</strong> 2101</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🏗️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Three roles</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Server pushes corrections to the caster. Client pulls from the caster. The caster multiplexes one stream to many clients simultaneously.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">HTTP under the hood</div>
          <div class="summary-body">NTRIP is an HTTP-based protocol — it works through firewalls and proxies that block raw TCP. Default port 2101. NTRIP v2 uses proper HTTP/1.1 chunked transfer.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📋</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Source table first</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Always fetch the source table before connecting. Check the format details field for message types and rates. Choose the mountpoint nearest your work area.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📍</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Send GGA for VRS</div>
          <div class="summary-body">VRS mountpoints need your position to generate tailored corrections. Configure your receiver to send GGA to the caster every 5–30 seconds.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/protocols/rtcm" class="nav-prev">← RTCM</a>
        <a href="/learn/protocols/binary-protocols" class="nav-next">Binary Protocols →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Weber, G., Dettmering, D. & Gebhard, H. (2005). Networked transport of RTCM via internet protocol (NTRIP). <em>IAG Symposia</em>, 128, 60–64.</li>
          <li>RTCM 10410.1 — NTRIP Version 2.0 Standard. <a href="https://www.rtcm.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtcm.org →</a></li>
          <li>BKG NTRIP Client (BNC) — open-source NTRIP client and data processor. <a href="https://igs.bkg.bund.de/ntrip/bnc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">BKG →</a></li>
          <li>rtk2go.com public caster. <a href="http://rtk2go.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtk2go.com →</a></li>
          <li>NOAA NGS CORS Network. <a href="https://geodesy.noaa.gov/CORS/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NGS →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }
  code { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; background: var(--bg3); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 3px; color: var(--accent2); }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout-warn { background: rgba(251,191,36,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(251,191,36,0.2); color: var(--text2); }
  .callout strong { color: var(--text); }

  /* Roles diagram */
  .roles-diagram { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr auto 1fr; gap: 10px; align-items: start; margin: 20px 0; }
  .role { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; }
  .role-server { border-top: 2px solid var(--accent2); }
  .role-caster { border-top: 2px solid #fbbf24; }
  .role-client { border-top: 2px solid var(--accent); }
  .role-icon { font-size: 22px; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .role-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--text); }
  .role-sub { font-size: 11px; font-family: var(--mono); color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .role-desc { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 8px; }
  .role-example { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); font-style: italic; }
  .role-arrow { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); padding-top: 40px; white-space: nowrap; }

  /* Steps */
  .steps { counter-reset: step; list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 16px 0; }
  .steps li { counter-increment: step; padding: 12px 12px 12px 48px; position: relative; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); font-size: 14px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.7; }
  .steps li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .steps li::before { content: counter(step); position: absolute; left: 12px; top: 14px; width: 22px; height: 22px; background: rgba(0,212,170,0.12); color: var(--accent); border-radius: 50%; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-family: var(--mono); }

  /* Code blocks */
  .code-block { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; overflow: hidden; margin: 14px 0; }
  .code-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); padding: 8px 14px; background: var(--bg3); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border); }
